{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621402"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:53:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:53:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16709"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16709"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0,0,0.78,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9400"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74740"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9400"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16709"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60224"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"4625"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9731"},{"type":"tags","id":"10387"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22252"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74740"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with acute onset right-sided weakness and inability to speak. She has a medical history of atrial fibrillation, hypertension, and type 2 diabetes. Her medications include Warfarin, Metformin, and Perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 110/min and irregular, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She has a dense right hemiparesis, right hemianopia, and right-sided sensory loss. She is unable to speak, follow commands, name objects, or write. CT brain reveals a large left middle cerebral artery territory infarct involving both frontal and posterior language areas.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely type of aphasia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Broca aphasia","Transcortical aphasia","Anomic aphasia","Global aphasia","Conduction aphasia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features consistent with a large left middle cerebral artery (MCA) territory stroke affecting both anterior and posterior language areas. The combination of impaired comprehension, expression, repetition, naming, and writing is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eglobal aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the most severe form of aphasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBroca aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with non-fluent speech but preserved comprehension. Patients can understand spoken language but have difficulty producing speech. This occurs with lesions primarily affecting the anterior language areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranscortical aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E can be motor (anterior lesion) or sensory (posterior lesion) type, but not both. These patients typically have preserved repetition despite other language deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnomic aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by isolated difficulty with naming objects while other language functions remain relatively intact. It typically occurs with smaller lesions and represents a milder form of aphasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConduction aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by impaired repetition with relatively preserved comprehension and fluent, though paraphasic, speech. It occurs with lesions affecting the arcuate fasciculus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlobal aphasia typically results from large MCA territory infarcts affecting both Broca\u0027s and Wernicke\u0027s areas, as seen in this case. The presence of right hemiparesis and hemianopia further supports an extensive MCA territory involvement. The likely underlying cause in this case is cardioembolic stroke from atrial fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Global aphasia results from large lesions affecting both anterior and posterior language areas in the dominant hemisphere.","Global aphasia presents with impairment of all language modalities including comprehension, fluency, repetition, naming, reading and writing.","Middle cerebral artery occlusion is a common cause of global aphasia due to its extensive territory of supply to language areas."],"references":["Li, Tt., Zhang, Pp., Zhang, Mc. et al. Meta-analysis and systematic review of the relationship between sex and the risk or incidence of poststroke aphasia and its types. BMC Geriatr 24, 220 (2024). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12877-024-04765-0","Sheppard SM, Sebastian R. Diagnosing and managing post-stroke aphasia. Expert Rev Neurother. 2021 Feb;21(2):221-234. doi: 10.1080/14737175.2020.1855976. Epub 2020 Dec 10. PMID: 33231117; PMCID: PMC7880889","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Tan, Y., Zhang, LM., Liang, Xl. et al. A literature review and meta-analysis of the optimal factors study of repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation in post-infarction aphasia. Eur J Med Res 29, 18 (2024). https://doi.org/10.1186/s40001-023-01525-5","Tippett DC, Niparko JK, Hillis AE. Aphasia: Current Concepts in Theory and Practice. J Neurol Transl Neurosci. 2014 Jan;2(1):1042. PMID: 24904925; PMCID: PMC4041294"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60224"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16709"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60224"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T18:11:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T18:11:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9400"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74740"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical st